[{"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0010\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.1</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0010\"></a>Common symptoms in multiple sclerosis.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00317.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0015\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.2</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0015\"></a>Internuclear ophthalmoplegia.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp9005\"></a>In this person left lateral gaze is normal <strong class=\"calibre8\">(A)</strong> but on attempted right lateral gaze, the left eye fails to adduct <strong class=\"calibre8\">(B).</strong> This is due to a lesion in the left MLF <strong class=\"calibre8\">(C)</strong> which prevents the right lateral gaze centre from communicating with the opposite oculomotor nucleus (which it needs to do to recruit the medial rectus muscle).</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0020\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.3</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0020\"></a>Clinical patterns of multiple sclerosis.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0025\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.4</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0025\"></a>An axial, T2-weighted MRI scan (A) and a fluid attenuation inversion recovery (FLAIR) sequence (B) in a patient with multiple sclerosis.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0030\"></a>There are numerous plaque-like lesions in the periventricular white matter, best seen on the FLAIR sequence [see text for explanation]. <span class=\"figcredit\">Courtesy of Dr Andrew MacKinnon.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00319.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0030\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.5</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0035\"></a>Oligoclonal bands in MS.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0040\"></a>The presence of oligoclonal bands of immunoglobulin G (IgG) in the CSF that are not present in the peripheral blood provides evidence of CNS inflammation.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00320.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0035\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.6</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0045\"></a>Delayed visual evoked potentials (VEPs) in MS.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00321.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0040\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.7</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0050\"></a>Fresh post-mortem brain specimen in multiple sclerosis showing salmon pink plaques in the periventricular white matter. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Stevens and Lowe: Pathology 2e (Mosby 2000) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00322.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0045\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.8</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0055\"></a>Sharply defined plaques of demyelination in (A) the periventricular white matter and (B) the brain stem.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0060\"></a>In this case the brain has been preserved in formaldehyde prior to slicing. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Prayson, R: Neuropathology (Chuchill Livingstone 2005) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00323.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0050\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.9</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0065\"></a>Appearances of a typical MS plaque with (A) a routine, haematoxylin and eosin or H&amp;E stain and (B) with the myelin stain Luxol fast blue (LFB).<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0070\"></a>Note the sharp peripheral margin with the surrounding normal white matter. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Stevens, A, Lowe, JS and Young: Wheater's Basic Histopathology 4e (Churchill Livingstone 2002) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0055\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.10</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0075\"></a>Balo's concentric sclerosis.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0080\"></a>The presence of multiple concentric rings of demyelinated and myelinated axons creates an \u2018onion skin\u2019 appearance [section of cerebral hemisphere; Loyez stain], in which myelin appears black. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Ellison, D and Love, S: Neuropathology 2e (Mosby 2003) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00324.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0060\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.11</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0085\"></a>Shadow plaques represent areas of remyelination (or partial remyelination) in multiple sclerosis.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0090\"></a>This section shows a shadow plaque (S) next to an area of active demyelination (D). Normal myelin (stained blue) can be seen at the far left-hand side of the image. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Ellison, D and Love, S: Neuropathology 2e (Mosby 2003) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00325.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0065\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.12</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0095\"></a>Geographical distribution of multiple sclerosis risk.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0100\"></a>Individuals who are closer to the equator below the age of 15 years are at a lower risk of MS in adulthood, regardless of subsequent migration.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00326.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0070\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.13</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0105\"></a>Axial MRI FLAIR images in a boy age 2 years 8 months with acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (ADEM).<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0110\"></a>There are patchy signal changes widely distributed in the cerebral white matter bilaterally, including diffuse involvement of the internal capsules. <span class=\"figcredit\">Courtesy of Dr Andrew MacKinnon.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0075\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.14</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0115\"></a>Foamy macrophages in an active MS plaque.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0120\"></a>Stained with oil red-O which highlights lipid. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Ellison, D and Love, S: Neuropathology 2e (Mosby 2003) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00327.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0080\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.15</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0125\"></a>Antigen recognition by CD4<sup class=\"calibre14\">+</sup> (helper) and CD8<sup class=\"calibre14\">+</sup> (cytotoxic) T-lymphocytes.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0130\"></a>The antigenic peptide (e.g. a myelin constituent) is first processed and presented by antigen-presenting cells.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00328.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0085\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.16</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0135\"></a>Conduction block and recovery of function in demyelinated axons. See text for explanation.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0090\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.17</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0140\"></a>Subtypes of active plaque in multiple sclerosis.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00330.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0095\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.18</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0145\"></a>An oligodendrocyte process investing part of an axon.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0150\"></a>The distal oligodendrocyte process (or para-axonal loop) is indicated. This is the target in \u2018dying-back\u2019 oligodendrogliopathy, the characteristic finding in pattern III multiple sclerosis plaques.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00331.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0100\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.19</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0155\"></a>Neurodegeneration in multiple sclerosis.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0160\"></a>In most patients, the early stages of MS are characterized by a relatively benign relapsing-remitting course with episodes of acute inflammatory demyelination and discrete clinical relapses, often with very good functional recovery. Most patients convert to a progressive phase of neurological decline, characterized by axonal loss (even in the normal-appearing white matter), together with plaques and neuronal loss in the cerebral cortex. The degenerative phase of MS is associated with brain atrophy and dilation of the ventricles.</figcaption>"}, {"image_source": "https://textbook-images-19283761293.s3.amazonaws.com/neuroscience/00316.jpeg", "image_caption": "<figcaption class=\"figleg\"><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"ca0105\"></a><span class=\"fignum\">Fig. 14.20</span> <a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0165\"></a>Cortical demyelination in multiple sclerosis.<br class=\"calibre7\"/><a class=\"calibre5\" id=\"sp0170\"></a>This image shows numerous plaques of demyelination (labelled \u201cd\u201d) at the cortical\u2013subcortical junction, within the cerebral cortex and in the subcortical white matter. A prominent area of subpial demyelination (labelled \u201csub\u201d) is also indicated. [Micrograph of the cerebral hemisphere; the tissue has been stained with Luxol fast blue, which is used to demonstrate myelin]. <span class=\"figcredit\">From Ellison, D and Love, S: Neuropathology 2e (Mosby 2003) with permission.</span></figcaption>"}]